# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fivetran-integration
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:fivetran-integration/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] The building blocks of data organization are tables and schemas.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Schema defines how tables consisting of rows and columns are linked to each other by primary and foreign keys.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Each Fivetran connector creates and manages its own schema.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] In simple terms, a Fivetran connector reaches out to your source, receives data from it, and writes it to your destination.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Depending on the type of connector, Fivetran either collects data that the source pushes to us or sends a request to the source and then grabs the data that the source sends in response.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] The following diagram displays a single connector of each of our supported connector types.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] In an ideal world, data analysts have access to all their required data without concern for where it's stored or how it's processed - analytics just works.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Until recently, the reality of analytics has been much more complicated.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Expensive data storage and underpowered data warehouses meant that accessing data involved building and maintaining fragile ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) pipelines that pre-aggregated and filtered data down to a consumable size.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] ETL software vendors competed on how customizable, and therefore specialized, their data pipelines were.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Technological advances now bring us closer to the analysts' ideal.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Practically free cloud data storage and dramatically more powerful modern columnar cloud data warehouses make fragile ETL pipelines a relic of the past.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Modern data architecture is ELT-extract and load the raw data into the destination, then transform it post-load.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] This difference has many benefits, including increased versatility and usability.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Read our blog post, The Modern Data Pipeline, to learn more about the difference between ETL and ELT.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Data transformation and modeling is a shared responsibility between Fivetran and you, the customer.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] 2. orchestrates the transformation, modeling, and validation within the destination.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] In designing a Fivetran schema, we do not try to provide an immediate answer to a specific customer's question.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Instead, our goal is to provide a correct, easy-to-query schema that all of our customers can use to answer their own questions.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] It is Fivetran’s responsibility to deliver up-to-date, accurate information in a cleaned and normalized schema - the canonical schema - at the lowest level of aggregation.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] It is our responsibility to regularly maintain the connector and evolve the canonical schema to reflect operational and product changes in the source systems.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] It is our responsibility to respond to any *unknown* operational breaking change in the extract and load from the source system to the destination schema.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] It is your responsibility to write SQL queries that transform and model the data we deliver into a format that's suited to your particular needs.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] It is your responsibility to regularly maintain the transformation and modeling as the canonical schema evolves.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] It is your responsibility to respond to a *known* operational breaking change and follow the instructions to restore service.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] In the cases we provide templates, like our dbt Core-compatible data models, we make sure that these templates are correct.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] However, you are responsible for adapting them to your needs.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Fivetran supports a standard list of data types for all our destinations.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Fivetran analyzes the source data to check whether the connector has specified the data type for a column.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] We select an appropriate data type for the data stored in that column before writing to your destination.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] We use our data type hierarchy to automatically assign the most appropriate data type.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] We compute the data subtype and supertype using our hierarchy.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] We also use our hierarchy to find the optimal data type to write the data to your destination.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Depending on the destination, we may need to transform a source data type to a supported destination data type.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] You can find more information about these transformations on Fivetran's destination pages.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] For example, if your source database specifies a column data type as JSON, but your destination doesn't have a native JSON type, we change the column’s data type from JSON to STRING so that we can create the column in the destination.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Fivetran has a defined subtype-supertype relationship among the data types.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] In our hierarchy, JSON and STRING are the largest data types.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] The data type hierarchy is universal across all the destinations we support.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] The following image illustrates Fivetran’s data type hierarchy.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Fivetran automatically assigns a data type when the source doesn't specify the data type.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] We try to use the smallest data type that can correctly store and represent your data.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Smaller data types are usually faster because they use less space on the disk and in memory and because they require fewer CPU cycles to process.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] We try to use the simplest data type because operations on simpler data types are comparatively faster.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] For example, INT is easier to compare than STRING.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] We use type inference and subtyping to find the optimal data type that we can use.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] We infer the data type by looking at each value and inferring the most specific type that can hold that value.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] The key principle behind using type inference is reversibility.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] For example, the STRING '9' can be coerced to the INT 9, then back to STRING, and we will get the original value, '9'.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] We make a few exceptions to the reversibility principle to infer the precise data types.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] For example, we will infer the data type of '9.90' to be DOUBLE, even though the coercion of '9.90' that results in 9.9 is not reversible.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] After inferring the data type for a value, we combine all the inferred data types according to our type hierarchy to find the optimal column data type.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] We use our data type hierarchy to identify subtypes and supertypes.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] With subtyping, we try to minimize the type that we choose while still preserving the data’s integrity from the source.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] For example, SHORT is a subtype of INT because every SHORT is also an INT.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] We use subtyping to use the smallest possible data type to store the data.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Each data type has a specific disk size.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] We transform the data type if the transformation does not result in a loss of precision.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] It lets us use less disk space to store the data in the destination.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] If the column's data type (specified by the connector or inferred by us) is different from the one in the destination, we use supertyping to find the appropriate column data type to write to the destination.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Combine the data type with the type in the destination according to our type hierarchy.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Merge the new data with the existing data in the destination.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Our philosophy is to make a faithful replication of source data with as few transformations as necessary to make it useful.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Fivetran automatically maps internal source types to supported destination types.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] There are a few types of transformations that Fivetran performs automatically before loading the data.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] The first type of transformation is a minimal data cleaning.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Perform a small amount of data manipulation and cleaning to put it in an optimal format to work within your destination.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] These textbook transformations are generally very generic and are beneficial for all of our customers.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Depending on how structured and well formatted the source data or API endpoints are, Fivetran performs some normalizing and cleaning of the schema.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Schema transformations happen on a connector by connector basis.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] For further information relating to a particular connector, check the schema section of its documentation page.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Fivetran does not support advanced or user-definable in-flight transformations before we load your data, except for the row filtering feature, which is supported as an in-flight transformation.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] We do support custom push-down transformations in the destination after your data is loaded.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Because transformations happen post-load in the destination, your raw data is always available along with the transformed data.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Read the Fivetran Transformations documentation to learn more about transformations in the destination.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Fivetran initially converts source timestamps to UTC and then loads them into your destination as UTC.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] However, if a source timestamp does not contain time zone information, then we load it as a TIMESTAMP WITHOUT TIMEZONE type into your destination.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] You can customize your connection's schema name when you first set up your connection.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] For more information, see our naming conventions documentation.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Fivetran automatically promotes the column type to the most specific data type that losslessly accepts both the old and new data.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] For example, if you convert a DOUBLE column to a BOOLEAN column, Fivetran converts the column to STRING which losslessly represents both the numbers and the strings "true" and "false." Note that column order might change when we convert column data types.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] We encourage customers to use VIEWs to enforce data type coercions.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Some sources, such as JSON files or MongoDB, are composed of JSON objects with unknown schemas.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] In these cases, Fivetran promotes first level fields to columns in your destination.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] If the first level field is a simple data type, we map it to its own type.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] If it's a complex data type (arrays or JSON data) we map it to a JSON type without unpacking.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] We do not automatically unpack nested JSON objects to separate tables in the destination.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Any nested JSON objects will be preserved as is in the destination, so you will be able to use JSON processing functions in the destination.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] When we re-sync a connection, we invalidate its incremental sync cursors, and we re-fetch all the original records from the source.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] A re-sync is exactly like an initial sync, except that rather than creating new rows or tables in the destination, we overwrite the existing rows in the tables.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] For the majority of data, this may seem wasteful because we overwrite the rows with the same contents they have in the destination.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] However, in cases where the continuity of incremental updates has broken, this is the only way to ensure that we don't miss any changed data (new, changed, or deleted rows).
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Whenever we write data to files stored locally on the disk or in the cloud, it is encrypted.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] During the sync, Fivetran checkpoints data.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] A checkpoint marks the point in the sync operation up to which data have been retrieved, and written to the destination.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] If your incremental sync fails, then Fivetran restarts the next sync from the last checkpoint, and not from point where the last successful sync left off.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] If your historical sync fails, then Fivetran restarts the next sync from the last checkpoint, not from the historical data start.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] All Fivetran connectors use checkpoints.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] The checkpoint specifics vary depending on the connector type and your source configuration.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] We release new features, connectors, and destinations in phases to ensure we provide our users with the highest-quality experience.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Below, we have outlined the expected user experience for each phase.
[src:fivetran-integration/core-concepts] Lite connectors have different release phases.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The decision to integrate data tends to arise when the volume, complexity (that is, big data) and need to share existing data explodes.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] It has become the focus of extensive theoretical work, and numerous open problems remain unsolved.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Data integration encourages collaboration between internal as well as external users.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The data being integrated must be received from a heterogeneous database system and transformed to a single coherent data store that provides synchronous data across a network of files for clients.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] A common use of data integration is in data mining when analyzing and extracting information from existing databases that can be useful for Business information.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Issues with combining heterogeneous data sources, often referred to as information silos, under a single query interface have existed for some time.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] In the early 1980s, computer scientists began designing systems for interoperability of heterogeneous databases.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The first data integration system driven by structured metadata was designed in 1991 at the University of Minnesota for the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] IPUMS used a data warehousing approach, which extracts, transforms, and loads data from heterogeneous sources into a unique view schema so data from different sources become compatible.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] By making thousands of population databases interoperable, IPUMS demonstrated the feasibility of large-scale data integration.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The data warehouse approach offers a tightly coupled architecture because the data are already physically reconciled in a single queryable repository, so it usually takes little time to resolve queries.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The data warehouse approach is less feasible for data sets that are frequently updated, requiring the extract, transform, load (ETL) process to be continuously re-executed for synchronization.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Difficulties also arise in constructing data warehouses when one has only a query interface to summary data sources and no access to the full data.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] This problem frequently emerges when integrating several commercial query services like travel or classified advertisement web applications.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] A trend began in 2009 favoring the loose coupling of data and providing a unified query-interface to access real time data over a mediated schema (see Figure 2), which allows information to be retrieved directly from original databases.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] This is consistent with the SOA approach popular in that era.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] This approach relies on mappings between the mediated schema and the schema of original sources, and translating a query into decomposed queries to match the schema of the original databases.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Such mappings can be specified in two ways: as a mapping from entities in the mediated schema to entities in the original sources (the "Global-as-View" (GAV) approach), or as a mapping from entities in the original sources to the mediated schema (the "Local-as-View" (LAV) approach).
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The latter approach requires more sophisticated inferences to resolve a query on the mediated schema, but makes it easier to add new data sources to a (stable) mediated schema.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] As of 2010, some of the work in data integration research concerns the semantic integration problem.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] This problem addresses not the structuring of the architecture of the integration, but how to resolve semantic conflicts between heterogeneous data sources.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] For example, if two companies merge their databases, certain concepts and definitions in their respective schemas like "earnings" inevitably have different meanings.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] In one database it may mean profits in dollars (a floating-point number), while in the other it might represent the number of sales (an integer).
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] A common strategy for the resolution of such problems involves the use of ontologies which explicitly define schema terms and thus help to resolve semantic conflicts.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] This approach represents ontology-based data integration.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] On the other hand, the problem of combining research results from different bioinformatics repositories requires bench-marking of the similarities, computed from different data sources, on a single criterion such as positive predictive value.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] This enables the data sources to be directly comparable and can be integrated even when the natures of experiments are distinct.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] As of 2011, it was determined that current data modeling methods were imparting data isolation into every data architecture in the form of islands of disparate data and information silos.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] This data isolation is an unintended artifact of the data modeling methodology that results in the development of disparate data models.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Disparate data models, when instantiated as databases, form disparate databases.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Enhanced data model methodologies have been developed to eliminate the data isolation artifact and to promote the development of integrated data models.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] One enhanced data modeling method recasts data models by augmenting them with structural metadata in the form of standardized data entities.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] As a result of recasting multiple data models, the set of recast data models will now share one or more commonality relationships that relate the structural metadata now common to these data models.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Commonality relationships are a peer-to-peer type of entity relationships that relate the standardized data entities of multiple data models.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Multiple data models that contain the same standard data entity may participate in the same commonality relationship.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] When integrated data models are instantiated as databases and are properly populated from a common set of master data, then these databases are integrated.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Since 2011, data hub approaches have been of greater interest than fully structured (typically relational) Enterprise Data Warehouses.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Since 2013, data lake approaches have risen to the level of Data Hubs.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] (See all three search terms popularity on Google Trends.) These approaches combine unstructured or varied data into one location, but do not necessarily require an (often complex) master relational schema to structure and define all data in the Hub.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Data integration plays a big role in business regarding data collection used for studying the market.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Converting the raw data retrieved from consumers into coherent data is something businesses try to do when considering what steps they should take next.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Organizations are more frequently using data mining for collecting information and patterns from their databases, and this process helps them develop new business strategies to increase business performance and perform economic analyses more efficiently.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Compiling the large amount of data they collect to be stored in their system is a form of data integration adapted for Business intelligence to improve their chances of success.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Consider a web application where a user can query a variety of information about cities (such as crime statistics, weather, hotels, demographics, etc.).
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Traditionally, the information must be stored in a single database with a single schema.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] But any single enterprise would find information of this breadth somewhat difficult and expensive to collect.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Even if the resources exist to gather the data, it would likely duplicate data in existing crime databases, weather websites, and census data.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] A data-integration solution may address this problem by considering these external resources as materialized views over a virtual mediated schema, resulting in "virtual data integration".
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] This means application-developers construct a virtual schema—the *mediated schema*—to best model the kinds of answers their users want.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Next, they design "wrappers" or adapters for each data source, such as the crime database and weather website.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] These adapters simply transform the local query results (those returned by the respective websites or databases) into an easily processed form for the data integration solution (see figure 2).
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] When an application-user queries the mediated schema, the data-integration solution transforms this query into appropriate queries over the respective data sources.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Finally, the virtual database combines the results of these queries into the answer to the user's query.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] This solution offers the convenience of adding new sources by simply constructing an adapter or an application software blade for them.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] It contrasts with ETL systems or with a single database solution, which require manual integration of entire new data set into the system.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The virtual ETL solutions leverage virtual mediated schema to implement data harmonization; whereby the data are copied from the designated "master" source to the defined targets, field by field.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Advanced data virtualization is also built on the concept of object-oriented modeling in order to construct virtual mediated schema or virtual metadata repository, using hub and spoke architecture.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Each data source is disparate and as such is not designed to support reliable joins between data sources.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Therefore, data virtualization as well as data federation depends upon accidental data commonality to support combining data and information from disparate data sets.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Because of the lack of data value commonality across data sources, the return set may be inaccurate, incomplete, and impossible to validate.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] One solution is to recast disparate databases to integrate these databases without the need for ETL.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The recast databases support commonality constraints where referential integrity may be enforced between databases.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The recast databases provide designed data access paths with data value commonality across databases.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The theory of data integration forms a subset of database theory and formalizes the underlying concepts of the problem in first-order logic.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Applying the theories gives indications as to the feasibility and difficulty of data integration.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] While its definitions may appear abstract, they have sufficient generality to accommodate all manner of integration systems, including those that include nested relational / XML databases and those that treat databases as programs.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Connections to particular databases systems such as Oracle or DB2 are provided by implementation-level technologies such as JDBC and are not studied at the theoretical level.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Data integration systems are formally defined as a tuple $\left\langle G,S,M\right\rangle$ where G is the global (or mediated) schema, S is the heterogeneous set of source schemas, and M is the mapping that maps queries between the source and the global schemas.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Both G and S are expressed in languages over alphabets composed of symbols for each of their respective relations.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The mapping M consists of assertions between queries over G and queries over S .
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] When users pose queries over the data integration system, they pose queries over G and the mapping then asserts connections between the elements in the global schema and the source schemas.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] A database over a schema is defined as a set of sets, one for each relation (in a relational database).
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The database corresponding to the source schema S would comprise the set of sets of tuples for each of the heterogeneous data sources and is called the *source database*.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Note that this single source database may actually represent a collection of disconnected databases.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The database corresponding to the virtual mediated schema G is called the *global database*.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The global database must satisfy the mapping M with respect to the source database.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The legality of this mapping depends on the nature of the correspondence between G and S .
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Two popular ways to model this correspondence exist: *Global as View* or GAV and *Local as View* or LAV.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] GAV systems model the global database as a set of views over S .
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] In this case M associates to each element of G a query over S .
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Query processing becomes a straightforward operation due to the well-defined associations between G and S .
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The burden of complexity falls on implementing mediator code instructing the data integration system exactly how to retrieve elements from the source databases.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] If any new sources join the system, considerable effort may be necessary to update the mediator, thus the GAV approach appears preferable when the sources seem unlikely to change.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] In a GAV approach to the example data integration system above, the system designer would first develop mediators for each of the city information sources and then design the global schema around these mediators.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] For example, consider if one of the sources served a weather website.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The designer would likely then add a corresponding element for weather to the global schema.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Then the bulk of effort concentrates on writing the proper mediator code that will transform predicates on weather into a query over the weather website.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] This effort can become complex if some other source also relates to weather, because the designer may need to write code to properly combine the results from the two sources.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] On the other hand, in LAV, the source database is modeled as a set of views over G .
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] In this case M associates to each element of S a query over G .
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Here the exact associations between G and S are no longer well-defined.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] As is illustrated in the next section, the burden of determining how to retrieve elements from the sources is placed on the query processor.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The benefit of an LAV modeling is that new sources can be added with far less work than in a GAV system, thus the LAV approach should be favored in cases where the mediated schema is less stable or likely to change.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] In an LAV approach to the example data integration system above, the system designer designs the global schema first and then simply inputs the schemas of the respective city information sources.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Consider again if one of the sources serves a weather website.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The designer would add corresponding elements for weather to the global schema only if none existed already.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Then programmers write an adapter or wrapper for the website and add a schema description of the website's results to the source schemas.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The complexity of adding the new source moves from the designer to the query processor.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The theory of query processing in data integration systems is commonly expressed using conjunctive queries and Datalog, a purely declarative logic programming language.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] One can loosely think of a conjunctive query as a logical function applied to the relations of a database such as " $f(A,B)$ where $A<B$ ".
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] If a tuple or set of tuples is substituted into the rule and satisfies it (makes it true), then we consider that tuple as part of the set of answers in the query.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] While formal languages like Datalog express these queries concisely and without ambiguity, common SQL queries count as conjunctive queries as well.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] In terms of data integration, "query containment" represents an important property of conjunctive queries.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] A query A contains another query B (denoted $A\supset B$ ) if the results of applying B are a subset of the results of applying A for any database.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The two queries are said to be equivalent if the resulting sets are equal for any database.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] This is important because in both GAV and LAV systems, a user poses conjunctive queries over a *virtual* schema represented by a set of views, or "materialized" conjunctive queries.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Integration seeks to rewrite the queries represented by the views to make their results equivalent or maximally contained by our user's query.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] This corresponds to the problem of answering queries using views (AQUV).
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] In GAV systems, a system designer writes mediator code to define the query-rewriting.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Each element in the user's query corresponds to a substitution rule just as each element in the global schema corresponds to a query over the source.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Query processing simply expands the subgoals of the user's query according to the rule specified in the mediator and thus the resulting query is likely to be equivalent.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] While the designer does the majority of the work beforehand, some GAV systems such as Tsimmis involve simplifying the mediator description process.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] In LAV systems, queries undergo a more radical process of rewriting because no mediator exists to align the user's query with a simple expansion strategy.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The integration system must execute a search over the space of possible queries in order to find the best rewrite.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The resulting rewrite may not be an equivalent query but maximally contained, and the resulting tuples may be incomplete.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] As of 2011 the GQR algorithm is the leading query rewriting algorithm for LAV data integration systems.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] In general, the complexity of query rewriting is NP-complete.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] If the space of rewrites is relatively small, this does not pose a problem — even for integration systems with hundreds of sources.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] Large-scale questions in science, such as real world evidence, global warming, invasive species spread, and resource depletion, are increasingly requiring the collection of disparate data sets for meta-analysis.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] This type of data integration is especially challenging for ecological and environmental data because metadata standards are not agreed upon and there are many different data types produced in these fields.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] National Science Foundation initiatives such as Datanet are intended to make data integration easier for scientists by providing cyberinfrastructure and setting standards.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The Research Data Alliance, has more recently explored creating global data integration frameworks.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-integration] The OpenPHACTS project, funded through the European Union Innovative Medicines Initiative, built a drug discovery platform by linking datasets from providers such as European Bioinformatics Institute, Royal Society of Chemistry, UniProt, WikiPathways and DrugBank.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] In computing, a **pipeline**, also known as a **data pipeline**, is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] The elements of a pipeline are often executed in parallel or in time-sliced fashion.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Some amount of buffer storage is often inserted between elements.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Pipelining is a commonly used concept in everyday life.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] For example, in the assembly line of a car factory, each specific task—such as installing the engine, installing the hood, and installing the wheels—is often done by a separate work station.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] The stations carry out their tasks in parallel, each on a different car.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Once a car has had one task performed, it moves to the next station.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Variations in the time needed to complete the tasks can be accommodated by "buffering" (holding one or more cars in a space between the stations) and/or by "stalling" (temporarily halting the upstream stations), until the next station becomes available.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Suppose that assembling one car requires three tasks that take 20, 10, and 15 minutes, respectively.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Then, if all three tasks were performed by a single station, the factory would output one car every 45 minutes.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] By using a pipeline of three stations, the factory would output the first car in 45 minutes, and then a new one every 20 minutes.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] As this example shows, pipelining does not decrease the latency, that is, the total time for one item to go through the whole system.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] It does however increase the system's throughput, that is, the rate at which new items are processed after the first one.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] In computing, a pipeline or data pipeline is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] If a pipeline consists of idempotent steps, these can be rerun without altering the outcome beyond the initial run.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] This is advantageous in terms of reliability and maintenance.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Since the throughput of a pipeline cannot be better than that of its slowest element, the designer should try to divide the work and resources among the stages so that they all take the same time to complete their tasks.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] In the car assembly example above, if the three tasks took 15 minutes each, instead of 20, 10, and 15 minutes, the latency would still be 45 minutes, but a new car would then be finished every 15 minutes, instead of 20.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Under ideal circumstances, if all processing elements are synchronized and take the same amount of time to process, then each item can be received by each element just as it is released by the previous one, in a single clock cycle.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] That way, the items will flow through the pipeline at a constant speed, like waves in a water channel.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] In such "wave pipelines", no synchronization or buffering is needed between the stages, besides the storage needed for the data items.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] More generally, buffering between the pipeline stages is necessary when the processing times are irregular, or when items may be created or destroyed along the pipeline.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] For example, in a graphics pipeline that processes triangles to be rendered on the screen, an element that checks the visibility of each triangle may discard the triangle if it is invisible, or may output two or more triangular pieces of the element if they are partly hidden.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Buffering is also needed to accommodate irregularities in the rates at which the application feeds items to the first stage and consumes the output of the last one.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] The buffer between two stages may be simply a hardware register with suitable synchronization and signalling logic between the two stages.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] When a stage A stores a data item in the register, it sends a "data available" signal to the next stage B.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Once B has used that data, it responds with a "data received" signal to A.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Stage A halts, waiting for this signal, before storing the next data item into the register.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Stage B halts, waiting for the "data available" signal, if it is ready to process the next item but stage A has not provided it yet.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] If the processing times of an element are variable, the whole pipeline may often have to stop, waiting for that element and all the previous ones to consume the items in their input buffers.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] The frequency of such pipeline stalls can be reduced by providing space for more than one item in the input buffer of that stage.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Such a multiple-item buffer is usually implemented as a first-in, first-out queue.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] The upstream stage may still have to be halted when the queue gets full, but the frequency of those events will decrease as more buffer slots are provided.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Queueing theory can tell the number of buffer slots needed, depending on the variability of the processing times and on the desired performance.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] If some stage takes (or may take) much longer than the others, and cannot be sped up, the designer can provide two or more processing elements to carry out that task in parallel, with a single input buffer and a single output buffer.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] As each element finishes processing its current data item, it delivers it to the common output buffer, and takes the next data item from the common input buffer.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] This concept of "non-linear" or "dynamic" pipeline is exemplified by shops or banks that have two or more cashiers serving clients from a single waiting queue.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] In some applications, the processing of an item Y by a stage A may depend on the results or effect of processing a previous item X by some later stage B of the pipeline.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] In that case, stage A cannot correctly process item Y until item X has cleared stage B.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] This situation occurs very often in instruction pipelines.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] For example, suppose that Y is an arithmetic instruction that reads the contents of a register that was supposed to have been modified by an earlier instruction X.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Let A be the stage that fetches the instruction operands, and B be the stage that writes the result to the specified register.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] If stage A tries to process instruction Y before instruction X reaches stage B, the register may still contain the old value, and the effect of Y would be incorrect.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] In order to handle such conflicts correctly, the pipeline must be provided with extra circuitry or logic that detects them and takes the appropriate action.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Rather than halt while waiting for X to be finished, stage A may guess whether the branch will be taken or not, and fetch the next instruction Y based on that guess.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] If the guess later turns out to be incorrect (hopefully rarely), the system would have to backtrack and resume with the correct choice.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] To be effectively implemented, data pipelines need a CPU scheduling strategy to dispatch work to the available CPU cores, and the usage of data structures on which the pipeline stages will operate on.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] For example, UNIX derivatives may pipeline commands connecting various processes' standard IO, using the pipes implemented by the operating system.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Some operating systems may provide UNIX-like syntax to string several program runs in a pipeline, but implement the latter as simple serial execution, rather than true pipelining—namely, by waiting for each program to finish before starting the next one.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Lower level approaches may rely on the threads provided by the operating system to schedule work on the stages: both thread pool-based implementations or on a one-thread-per-stage are viable, and exist.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Other strategies relying on cooperative multitasking exist, that do not need multiple threads of execution and hence additional CPU cores, such as using a round-robin scheduler with a coroutine-based framework.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] In this context, each stage may be instantiated with its own coroutine, yielding control back to the scheduler after finishing its round task.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] This approach may need careful control over the process' stages to avoid them abuse their time slice.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] A pipelined system typically requires more resources (circuit elements, processing units, computer memory, etc.) than one that executes one batch at a time, because its stages cannot share those resources, and because buffering and additional synchronization logic may be needed between the elements.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Moreover, the transfer of items between separate processing elements may increase the latency, especially for long pipelines.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] The additional complexity cost of pipelining may be considerable if there are dependencies between the processing of different items, especially if a guess-and-backtrack strategy is used to handle them.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Indeed, the cost of implementing that strategy for complex instruction sets has motivated some radical proposals to simplify computer architecture, such as RISC and VLIW.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] Compilers also have been burdened with the task of rearranging the machine instructions so as to improve the performance of instruction pipelines.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] In recent years the demands on applications and their underlying hardware have been significant.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] For example, building pipelines with single node applications that trawl through the data row by row is no longer feasible with the volume and variety of big data.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] However, with the advent of data analytics engines such as Hadoop, or more recently Apache Spark, it's been possible to distribute large datasets across multiple processing nodes, allowing applications to reach heights of efficiency several hundred times greater than was thought possible before.
[src:fivetran-integration/data-pipeline] The effect of this today is that even a mid-level PC using distributed processing in this fashion can handle the building and running of big data pipelines.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] A properly designed ETL system extracts data from source systems and enforces data type and data validity standards and ensures it conforms structurally to the requirements of the output.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems can also deliver data in a presentation-ready format so that application developers can build applications and end users can make decisions.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] The ETL process is often used in data warehousing.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] ETL systems commonly integrate data from multiple applications (systems), typically developed and supported by different vendors or hosted on separate computer hardware.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] The separate systems containing the original data are frequently managed and operated by different stakeholders.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] For example, a cost accounting system may combine data from payroll, sales, and purchasing.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] ETL and its variant ELT (extract, load, transform), are increasingly used in cloud-based data warehousing.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Applications involve not only batch processing, but also real-time streaming.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] ETL processing involves extracting the data from the source system(s).
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] In many cases, this represents the most important aspect of ETL, since extracting data correctly sets the stage for the success of subsequent processes.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Most data-warehousing projects combine data from different source systems.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Each separate system may also use a different data organization and/or format.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] The streaming of the extracted data source and loading on-the-fly to the destination database is another way of performing ETL when no intermediate data storage is required.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] An intrinsic part of the extraction involves data validation to confirm whether the data pulled from the sources has the correct/expected values in a given domain (such as a pattern/default or list of values).
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] If the data fails the validation rules, it is rejected entirely or in part.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] The rejected data is ideally reported back to the source system for further analysis to identify and to rectify incorrect records or perform data wrangling.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] In the data transformation stage, a series of rules or functions are applied to the extracted data in order to prepare it for loading into the end target.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] An important function of transformation is data cleansing, which aims to pass only "proper" data to the target.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] The challenge when different systems interact is in the relevant systems' interfacing and communicating.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Character sets that may be available in one system may not be in others.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] The load phase loads the data into the end target, which can be any data store including a simple delimited flat file or a data warehouse.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Depending on the requirements of the organization, this process varies widely.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Some data warehouses may overwrite existing information with cumulative information; updating extracted data is frequently done on a daily, weekly, or monthly basis.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Other data warehouses (or even other parts of the same data warehouse) may add new data in a historical form at regular intervals – for example, hourly.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] To understand this, consider a data warehouse that is required to maintain sales records of the last year.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] This data warehouse overwrites any data older than a year with newer data.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] However, the entry of data for any one year window is made in a historical manner.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] The timing and scope to replace or append are strategic design choices dependent on the time available and the business needs.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] More complex systems can maintain a history and audit trail of all changes to the data loaded in the data warehouse.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] As the load phase interacts with a database, the constraints defined in the database schema – as well as in triggers activated upon data load – apply (for example, uniqueness, referential integrity, mandatory fields), which also contribute to the overall data quality performance of the ETL process.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Audit reports (for example, on compliance with business rules.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Archive (Extreme, space-efficient compression for very rarely used, old data.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] ETL processes can involve considerable complexity, and significant operational problems can occur with improperly designed ETL systems.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] The range of data values or data quality in an operational system may exceed the expectations of designers at the time validation and transformation rules are specified.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Data profiling of a source during data analysis can identify the data conditions that must be managed by transform rules specifications, leading to an amendment of validation rules explicitly and implicitly implemented in the ETL process.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Data warehouses are typically assembled from a variety of data sources with different formats and purposes.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] As such, ETL is a key process to bring all the data together in a standard, homogeneous environment.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Design analysis should establish the scalability of an ETL system across the lifetime of its usage – including understanding the volumes of data that must be processed within service level agreements.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] The time available to extract from source systems may change, which may mean the same amount of data may have to be processed in less time.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems have to scale to process terabytes of data to update data warehouses with tens of terabytes of data.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Increasing volumes of data may require designs that can scale from daily batch to multiple-day micro batch to integration with message queues or real-time change-data-capture for continuous transformation and update.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Unique keys play an important part in all relational databases, as they tie everything together.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] A unique key is a column that identifies a given entity, whereas a foreign key is a column in another table that refers to a primary key.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Keys can comprise several columns, in which case they are composite keys.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] In many cases, the primary key is an auto-generated integer that has no meaning for the business entity being represented, but solely exists for the purpose of the relational database – commonly referred to as a surrogate key.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] As there is usually more than one data source getting loaded into the warehouse, the keys are an important concern to be addressed.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] For example: customers might be represented in several data sources, with their Social Security number as the primary key in one source, their phone number in another, and a surrogate in the third.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Yet a data warehouse may require the consolidation of all the customer information into one dimension.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] A recommended way to deal with the concern involves adding a warehouse surrogate key, which is used as a foreign key from the fact table.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Usually, updates occur to a dimension's source data, which must be reflected in the data warehouse.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] If the primary key of the source data is required for reporting, the dimension already contains that piece of information for each row.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] If the source data uses a surrogate key, the warehouse must keep track of it even though it is never used in queries or reports; it is done by creating a lookup table that contains the warehouse surrogate key and the originating key.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] This way, the dimension is not polluted with surrogates from various source systems, while the ability to update is preserved.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] The lookup table is used in different ways depending on the nature of the source data.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] A new dimension row is added with the new state of the source system, while the previous dimension row is updated to reflect it is no longer active and time of deactivation.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] ETL vendors benchmark their record-systems at multiple TB (terabytes) per hour (or ~1 GB per second) using powerful servers with multiple CPUs, multiple hard drives, multiple gigabit-network connections, and much memory.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] In real life, the slowest part of an ETL process usually occurs in the database load phase.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Databases may perform slowly because they have to take care of concurrency, integrity maintenance, and indices.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Still, even using bulk operations, database access is usually the bottleneck in the ETL process.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Whether to do certain operations in the database or outside may involve a trade-off.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] For example, removing duplicates using `distinct` may be slow in the database; thus, it makes sense to do it outside.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] On the other side, if using `distinct` significantly (x100) decreases the number of rows to be extracted, then it makes sense to remove duplications as early as possible in the database before unloading data.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] A common source of problems in ETL is a big number of dependencies among ETL jobs.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] For example, job "B" cannot start while job "A" is not finished.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] One can usually achieve better performance by visualizing all processes on a graph, and trying to reduce the graph making maximum use of parallelism, and making "chains" of consecutive processing as short as possible.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Again, partitioning of big tables and their indices can really help.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Another common issue occurs when the data are spread among several databases, and processing is done in those databases sequentially.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Sometimes database replication may be involved as a method of copying data between databases – it can significantly slow down the whole process.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] This approach allows processing to take maximum advantage of parallelism.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] For example, if you need to load data into two databases, you can run the loads in parallel (instead of loading into the first – and then replicating into the second).
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Sometimes processing must take place sequentially.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] For example, dimensional (reference) data are needed before one can get and validate the rows for main "fact" tables.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Some ETL software implementations include parallel processing.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] This enables a number of methods to improve overall performance of ETL when dealing with large volumes of data.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] All three types of parallelism usually operate combined in a single job or task.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] An additional difficulty comes with making sure that the data being uploaded is relatively consistent.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Because multiple source databases may have different update cycles (some may be updated every few minutes, while others may take days or weeks), an ETL system may be required to hold back certain data until all sources are synchronized.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Likewise, where a warehouse may have to be reconciled to the contents in a source system or with the general ledger, establishing synchronization and reconciliation points becomes necessary.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Data warehousing procedures usually subdivide a big ETL process into smaller pieces running sequentially or in parallel.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] To keep track of data flows, it makes sense to tag each data row with "row_id", and tag each piece of the process with "run_id".
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] In case of a failure, having these IDs help to roll back and rerun the failed piece.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Best practice also calls for *checkpoints*, which are states when certain phases of the process are completed.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Once at a checkpoint, it is a good idea to write everything to disk, clean out some temporary files, log the state, etc.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] An established ETL framework may improve connectivity and scalability.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] A good ETL tool must be able to communicate with the many different relational databases and read the various file formats used throughout an organization.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] ETL tools have started to migrate into enterprise application integration, or even enterprise service bus, systems that now cover much more than just the extraction, transformation, and loading of data.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Many ETL vendors now have data profiling, data quality, and metadata capabilities.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] A common use case for ETL tools include converting CSV files to formats readable by relational databases.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] A typical translation of millions of records is facilitated by ETL tools that enable users to input CSV-like data feeds/files and import them into a database with as little code as possible.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] ETL tools are typically used by a broad range of professionals – from students in computer science looking to quickly import large data sets to database architects in charge of company account management, ETL tools have become a convenient tool that can be relied on to get maximum performance.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] ETL tools in most cases contain a GUI that helps users conveniently transform data, using a visual data mapper, as opposed to writing large programs to parse files and modify data types.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] While ETL tools have traditionally been for developers and IT staff, research firm Gartner wrote that the new trend is to provide these capabilities to business users so they can themselves create connections and data integrations when needed, rather than going to the IT staff.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Gartner refers to these non-technical users as Citizen Integrators.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] In online transaction processing (OLTP) applications, changes from individual OLTP instances are detected and logged into a snapshot, or batch, of updates.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] An ETL instance can be used to periodically collect all of these batches, transform them into a common format, and load them into a data lake or warehouse.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Data virtualization can be used to advance ETL processing.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] The application of data virtualization to ETL allowed solving the most common ETL tasks of data migration and application integration for multiple dispersed data sources.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Virtual ETL operates with the abstracted representation of the objects or entities gathered from the variety of relational, semi-structured, and unstructured data sources.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] ETL tools can leverage object-oriented modeling and work with entities' representations persistently stored in a centrally located hub-and-spoke architecture.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Such a collection that contains representations of the entities or objects gathered from the data sources for ETL processing is called a metadata repository and it can reside in memory or be made persistent.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] By using a persistent metadata repository, ETL tools can transition from one-time projects to persistent middleware, performing data harmonization and data profiling consistently and in near-real time.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Extract, load, transform (ELT) is a variant of ETL where the extracted data is loaded into the target system first.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] The architecture for the analytics pipeline shall also consider where to cleanse and enrich data as well as how to conform dimensions.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Some of the benefits of an ELT process include speed and the ability to more easily handle both unstructured and structured data.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Ralph Kimball and Joe Caserta's book *The Data Warehouse ETL Toolkit*, (Wiley, 2004), which is used as a textbook for courses teaching ETL processes in data warehousing, addressed this issue.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Cloud-based data warehouses like Amazon Redshift, Google BigQuery, Microsoft Azure Synapse Analytics, and Snowflake provide highly scalable computing power.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] This lets businesses forgo preload transformations and replicate raw data into their data warehouses, where it can transform them as needed using SQL.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] After having used ELT, data may be processed further and stored in a data mart.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Most data integration tools skew towards ETL, while ELT is popular in database and data warehouse appliances.
[src:fivetran-integration/extract-transform-load] Similarly, it is possible to perform TEL (Transform, Extract, Load) where data is first transformed on a blockchain (as a way of recording changes to data, e.g., token burning) before extracting and loading into another data store.
